Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the Chime project.

## What was implemented:

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 (latest) using npm
- Updated package.json with the new dependency
- Updated package-lock.json to ensure consistent dependency resolution

### 2. Analytics Integration
- Added Analytics component import from '@vercel/analytics/next' in src/app/layout.tsx
- Placed the <Analytics /> component at the end of the <body> tag in the root layout
- This follows the official Vercel documentation for Next.js App Router setup

### 3. Modified Files:
- web/package.json - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- web/package-lock.json - Updated with new package dependencies
- web/src/app/layout.tsx - Added Analytics import and component

## Implementation Details:

The project uses Next.js 16.2.10 with the App Router pattern. Following the official Vercel Web Analytics documentation retrieved from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart, I:

1. Installed the analytics package using npm (as indicated by the presence of package-lock.json)
2. Added the Analytics component from '@vercel/analytics/next' to the root layout
3. Placed the component inside the body tag, after the existing content (SkipLink and Providers)
4. Verified the implementation with a successful production build and linter check

## Testing & Verification:

✅ Build completed successfully (npm run build)
✅ Linter passed with no errors (npm run lint)
✅ TypeScript compilation passed during build
✅ All 34 routes generated successfully

## Next Steps:

To activate Web Analytics:
1. Deploy the application to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard under the project's Analytics section
3. After deployment, analytics data will begin collecting automatically
4. Monitor the Network tab for requests to verify tracking is active

The Analytics component will automatically track page views and send analytics data to Vercel when the application is deployed.
